WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello and welcome to 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
I'm Beth.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Neil.

6
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Today we're going to talk about climate change

7
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:20.000
and how it can affect people's mental health.

8
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Natural disasters and the impacts of climate change

9
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
can be stressful isn't that right, Beth.

10
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Yeah, definitely.

11
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.000
In today's episode, we're going to find out about how people can protect

12
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
their mental health from the impacts of climate change.

13
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
We'll be hearing from a psychiatry expert and a man who survived a wildfire

14
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.000
and helped rebuild his town.

15
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
But first, Beth, I have a question for you.

16
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Scientists aren't always sure where the natural disasters like floods and wildfires

17
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
are as a result of human cause to climate change.

18
00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:00.000
But in January 2025, big wildfires affected big parts of Los Angeles in California.

19
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
But according to the research organization, world weather attribution,

20
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.000
human cause climate change made the fires a 10% more likely.

21
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.000
B 35% more likely, or c 20% less likely.

22
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
I'm going to say 10% more likely.

23
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Okay, well, we'll find out the answer at the end of the program.

24
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Now, natural disasters like floods and wildfires can destroy homes and communities.

25
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:33.000
People who live in areas affected by natural disasters can often experience climate trauma.

26
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Trauma is what we call the very bad and long-lasting emotional effects of an event or experience.

27
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Professor Jati Misra is an expert in climate trauma at the University of California.

28
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
She explained more about the condition to Grey Jackson,

29
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
host of BBC World Service program for climate question.

30
00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Climate trauma is not an individual trauma.

31
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:02.000
It's a community wide trauma, which really requires community wide healing.

32
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Yeah, I'm really struck by what you've said about the fact that it's whole communities that are affected,

33
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:16.000
not individuals, but also part of the solution is about the community and how it rebuild and re-nits together.

34
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Absolutely, yes.

35
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:30.000
So we've found that individuals who have a greater sense of positive support from their family and a greater sense of meaningful connection with their community,

36
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
they are in general more resilient.

37
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:41.000
Jati's research on climate trauma has found that it affects communities rather than individuals.

38
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Host of the program, Grey Jackson, is struck by what Jati says.

39
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:50.000
If you're struck by an idea, you find it particularly interesting or impressive.

40
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Grey says that part of the solution to climate trauma could be in how the community re-nits together.

41
00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:01.000
This means how the social connections in a community are restored.

42
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:07.000
We can often describe a community as close knit, which means everyone helps and supports each other.

43
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Jati explains that having a strong community also helps reduce or heal climate trauma.

44
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:21.000
She says that researchers found that people who have a strong community are more resilient when bad things like natural disasters happen.

45
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:27.000
If you're resilient, you're able to get better, more easily after something difficult or bad happens.

46
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.000
One person who had to be resilient is Brad Sherwood.

47
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:37.000
He survived a wildfire in northern California in 2017 called the Tub Spire.

48
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
But when he returned home, his neighborhood was destroyed.

49
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:48.000
Brad started to volunteer for a local support network called after the fire to try to rebuild his community.

50
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
As he explained to BBC World Service program, the climate question.

51
00:03:52.000 --> 00:04:02.000
The silver lining in all this, I mean if it wasn't for the Tub Spire, we wouldn't be working as a community right now to build a new community plaza.

52
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:10.000
We were a close community before the Tubbs, but afterwards we are so much stronger in resilient.

53
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And I think our children are as well. They can jump over any hurdle.

54
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:22.000
Brad says that the work to rebuild and improve his community is the silver lining to the fire.

55
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:28.000
The expression silver lining means a positive thing that comes from a negative situation.

56
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Brad's community became more resilient after the fire, including the children.

57
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
He says that they can jump over any hurdle.

58
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
We can describe challenges or difficult things in life as hurdles.

59
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:47.000
And it's quite inspiring, I think, to hear how Brad has taken a bad situation and tried to stay resilient.

60
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Now the organization that Brad volunteers for after the fire are helping those impacted by the fires in LA in January.

61
00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Which reminds me, I asked you Beth about the impacts of human-made climate change on the wildfires in LA in January.

62
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.000
And I said 10% more likely.

63
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Which was, I'm afraid the wrong answer, it was actually 35%.

64
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Wow. Okay, well let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with trauma, which is what we call the very bad and long lasting emotional effects of an event or experience.

65
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:28.000
If you're struck by an idea or something someone has said, you find it particularly interesting or impressive.

66
00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
If a community re-nits together, it becomes closer again.

67
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
And a close-knit community is where everyone looks after each other.

68
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.000
Resilient means able to get better, more easily when bad things happen.

69
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:46.000
A silver lining is a positive thing that comes from a negative situation.

70
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And we can describe challenges or difficult things in life as hurdles.

71
